{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JZmCRc8e4u15PJhPmc1eay","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! I have thoroughly read the file. Here's a comprehensive breakdown of the patterns and structure you need to follow:\n\n## Key Query Patterns\n\n**Tagged Template Literals with postgres.js:**\n- Queries use backtick template literals with the `sql` object (from the `postgres` package)\n- Example: `` sql`SELECT * FROM rounds WHERE pda = ${pda}` ``\n- Dynamic values are interpolated directly: `${paramValue}`\n- **This is safe** — `postgres` handles parameterization/escaping automatically\n\n**Type Annotations:**\n- Every query result is typed: `` sql<TypeName[]>`...` ``\n- Example: `` sql<Round[]>`SELECT * FROM rounds...` ``\n- This ensures TypeScript enforces correct return types\n\n## Key Pattern Examples from the File\n\n**INSERT with RETURNING:**\n```typescript\nasync insertRound(params) {\n  const rows = await sql<Round[]>`\n    INSERT INTO rounds (pda, game, creator, ...)\n    VALUES (${params.pda}, ${params.game}, ...)\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return normalizeRound(rows[0]!);\n}\n```\n\n**UPDATE with RETURNING:**\n```typescript\nasync updateRoundPhase(pda, newPhase, updates) {\n  const rows = await sql<Round[]>`\n    UPDATE rounds SET\n      phase = ${newPhase},\n      updated_at = now(),\n      target_slot = COALESCE(${updates?.target_slot ?? null}, target_slot),\n      ...\n    WHERE pda = ${pda}\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return normalizeRound(rows[0]!);\n}\n```\n\n**SELECT with optional filtering:**\n```typescript\nasync getTransactions(wallet, cursor, limit = 20, game) {\n  const effectiveLimit = Math.min(limit, 50);\n  if (cursor && game) {\n    const rows = await sql<Transaction[]>`\n      SELECT * FROM transactions\n      WHERE wallet = ${wallet} AND id < ${cursor} AND game = ${game}\n      ORDER BY id DESC\n      LIMIT ${effectiveLimit}\n    `;\n    return rows.map(normalizeTransaction);\n  }\n  // ... other branches for different filters\n}\n```\n\n**JSON Handling (JSONB columns):**\n```typescript\n// INSERT with JSON:\n${params.entries ? sql.json(params.entries) : null}\n\n// UPDATE with JSON:\nentries = ${sql.json(entries)},\ngreen_entries = COALESCE(${updates.greenEntries ? sql.json(updates.greenEntries) : null}, green_entries)\n```\n\n## Type Definition Patterns\n\n**Interface for DB table (snake_case fields matching DB):**\n```typescript\nexport interface Transaction {\n  id: string;\n  wallet: string;\n  game: string;\n  match_id: string;        // Note: snake_case matches column names\n  tx_type: TransactionType;\n  amount_lamports: number;\n  tx_sig: string;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n```\n\n**Interface for input params (camelCase):**\n```typescript\nexport interface InsertTransactionParams {\n  wallet: string;\n  game: string;\n  matchId: string;         // Note: camelCase for input\n  txType: TransactionType;\n  amountLamports: number;\n  txSig: string;\n}\n```\n\n**Type union for enum-like values:**\n```typescript\nexport type TransactionType = \"deposit\" | \"payout\" | \"refund\";\nexport type RoundPhase = \"created\" | \"locked\" | \"settling\" | \"settled\" | \"expired\";\n```\n\n## Normalization Helper Pattern\n\nNumbers from the database need to be converted from strings (for large numbers):\n\n```typescript\nfunction normalizeTransaction(row: Transaction): Transaction {\n  return {\n    ...row,\n    amount_lamports: Number(row.amount_lamports),\n  };\n}\n\nfunction normalizeReferralEarning(row: ReferralEarning): ReferralEarning {\n  return {\n    ...row,\n    wager_lamports: Number(row.wager_lamports),\n    fee_lamports: Number(row.fee_lamports),\n    referrer_earned_lamports: Number(row.referrer_earned_lamports),\n    // ... more Number() conversions\n  };\n}\n```\n\n## Batch Insert Pattern\n\n```typescript\nasync insertTransactions(params) {\n  if (params.length === 0) return;\n  const values = params.map((p) => ({\n    wallet: p.wallet,\n    game: p.game,\n    match_id: p.matchId,  // Convert camelCase → snake_case\n    tx_type: p.txType,\n    amount_lamports: p.amountLamports,\n    tx_sig: p.txSig,\n  }));\n  await sql`\n    INSERT INTO transactions ${sql(values, \"wallet\", \"game\", \"match_id\", \"tx_type\", \"amount_lamports\", \"tx_sig\")}\n    ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING\n  `;\n}\n```\n\n## Existing Profile-Related Code\n\nThe file defines a **PlayerProfile interface** (lines 186-196):\n\n```typescript\nexport interface PlayerProfile {\n  id: number;\n  user_id: string;\n  wallet: string;\n  username: string;\n  username_updated_at: Date | null;\n  avatar_url: string | null;\n  heat_multiplier: number;\n  points_balance: number;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n```\n\n**Note:** There are NO database functions for PlayerProfile in this file yet — this is just the type definition. The `generateUsername` is imported from utilities but not used here.\n\n## Error Handling Pattern\n\nErrors are thrown directly when validation fails:\n```typescript\nconst current = await sql<Pick<Round, \"phase\">[]>`SELECT phase FROM rounds WHERE pda = ${pda}`;\nif (current.length === 0) {\n  throw new Error(`Round not found: ${pda}`);\n}\n```\n\n## General Structure\n\n1. **Imports** (lines 8-9) — postgres library + utilities\n2. **Type exports** (lines 15-196) — all public types with clear naming conventions\n3. **Helper functions** (lines 200-493) — phase validation, normalization functions\n4. **createDb factory function** (line 492+) — returns a Db interface implementation\n5. **Async methods** — all database operations are async, return Promises\n6. **Exports** — types and createDb function only (no direct sql export)\n\nThis modular pattern keeps the database layer isolated and fully typed!"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4603cf5e-2eec-42a2-ba7b-9521091bfde1","uuid":"d3eaf790-f51f-4939-8e9e-5ce271375323","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:51:46.702Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Read the file `/workspaces/rng-utopia/backend/services/backend/src/db.ts` thoroughly. I need to understand:\n1. The existing query patterns (how functions are structured, what `sql` object is used, how types are defined)\n2. How existing types like transaction types are defined (e.g., the `insertUserTransaction` function and `getUserTransactions`)\n3. Any existing profile-related code\n4. The general structure — imports at top, type definitions, function exports, etc.\n\nReport the full content of the file or at least the key patterns I need to follow. Focus on:\n- How queries are written (tagged template literals? prepared statements?)\n- How types are defined and exported\n- Error handling patterns\n- The function signature pattern used\n\nReport in detail so I can write matching code.","agentId":"a5e08ba9ebbd9f71d","agentType":"Explore","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent! I have thoroughly read the file. Here's a comprehensive breakdown of the patterns and structure you need to follow:\n\n## Key Query Patterns\n\n**Tagged Template Literals with postgres.js:**\n- Queries use backtick template literals with the `sql` object (from the `postgres` package)\n- Example: `` sql`SELECT * FROM rounds WHERE pda = ${pda}` ``\n- Dynamic values are interpolated directly: `${paramValue}`\n- **This is safe** — `postgres` handles parameterization/escaping automatically\n\n**Type Annotations:**\n- Every query result is typed: `` sql<TypeName[]>`...` ``\n- Example: `` sql<Round[]>`SELECT * FROM rounds...` ``\n- This ensures TypeScript enforces correct return types\n\n## Key Pattern Examples from the File\n\n**INSERT with RETURNING:**\n```typescript\nasync insertRound(params) {\n  const rows = await sql<Round[]>`\n    INSERT INTO rounds (pda, game, creator, ...)\n    VALUES (${params.pda}, ${params.game}, ...)\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return normalizeRound(rows[0]!);\n}\n```\n\n**UPDATE with RETURNING:**\n```typescript\nasync updateRoundPhase(pda, newPhase, updates) {\n  const rows = await sql<Round[]>`\n    UPDATE rounds SET\n      phase = ${newPhase},\n      updated_at = now(),\n      target_slot = COALESCE(${updates?.target_slot ?? null}, target_slot),\n      ...\n    WHERE pda = ${pda}\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return normalizeRound(rows[0]!);\n}\n```\n\n**SELECT with optional filtering:**\n```typescript\nasync getTransactions(wallet, cursor, limit = 20, game) {\n  const effectiveLimit = Math.min(limit, 50);\n  if (cursor && game) {\n    const rows = await sql<Transaction[]>`\n      SELECT * FROM transactions\n      WHERE wallet = ${wallet} AND id < ${cursor} AND game = ${game}\n      ORDER BY id DESC\n      LIMIT ${effectiveLimit}\n    `;\n    return rows.map(normalizeTransaction);\n  }\n  // ... other branches for different filters\n}\n```\n\n**JSON Handling (JSONB columns):**\n```typescript\n// INSERT with JSON:\n${params.entries ? sql.json(params.entries) : null}\n\n// UPDATE with JSON:\nentries = ${sql.json(entries)},\ngreen_entries = COALESCE(${updates.greenEntries ? sql.json(updates.greenEntries) : null}, green_entries)\n```\n\n## Type Definition Patterns\n\n**Interface for DB table (snake_case fields matching DB):**\n```typescript\nexport interface Transaction {\n  id: string;\n  wallet: string;\n  game: string;\n  match_id: string;        // Note: snake_case matches column names\n  tx_type: TransactionType;\n  amount_lamports: number;\n  tx_sig: string;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n```\n\n**Interface for input params (camelCase):**\n```typescript\nexport interface InsertTransactionParams {\n  wallet: string;\n  game: string;\n  matchId: string;         // Note: camelCase for input\n  txType: TransactionType;\n  amountLamports: number;\n  txSig: string;\n}\n```\n\n**Type union for enum-like values:**\n```typescript\nexport type TransactionType = \"deposit\" | \"payout\" | \"refund\";\nexport type RoundPhase = \"created\" | \"locked\" | \"settling\" | \"settled\" | \"expired\";\n```\n\n## Normalization Helper Pattern\n\nNumbers from the database need to be converted from strings (for large numbers):\n\n```typescript\nfunction normalizeTransaction(row: Transaction): Transaction {\n  return {\n    ...row,\n    amount_lamports: Number(row.amount_lamports),\n  };\n}\n\nfunction normalizeReferralEarning(row: ReferralEarning): ReferralEarning {\n  return {\n    ...row,\n    wager_lamports: Number(row.wager_lamports),\n    fee_lamports: Number(row.fee_lamports),\n    referrer_earned_lamports: Number(row.referrer_earned_lamports),\n    // ... more Number() conversions\n  };\n}\n```\n\n## Batch Insert Pattern\n\n```typescript\nasync insertTransactions(params) {\n  if (params.length === 0) return;\n  const values = params.map((p) => ({\n    wallet: p.wallet,\n    game: p.game,\n    match_id: p.matchId,  // Convert camelCase → snake_case\n    tx_type: p.txType,\n    amount_lamports: p.amountLamports,\n    tx_sig: p.txSig,\n  }));\n  await sql`\n    INSERT INTO transactions ${sql(values, \"wallet\", \"game\", \"match_id\", \"tx_type\", \"amount_lamports\", \"tx_sig\")}\n    ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING\n  `;\n}\n```\n\n## Existing Profile-Related Code\n\nThe file defines a **PlayerProfile interface** (lines 186-196):\n\n```typescript\nexport interface PlayerProfile {\n  id: number;\n  user_id: string;\n  wallet: string;\n  username: string;\n  username_updated_at: Date | null;\n  avatar_url: string | null;\n  heat_multiplier: number;\n  points_balance: number;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n```\n\n**Note:** There are NO database functions for PlayerProfile in this file yet — this is just the type definition. The `generateUsername` is imported from utilities but not used here.\n\n## Error Handling Pattern\n\nErrors are thrown directly when validation fails:\n```typescript\nconst current = await sql<Pick<Round, \"phase\">[]>`SELECT phase FROM rounds WHERE pda = ${pda}`;\nif (current.length === 0) {\n  throw new Error(`Round not found: ${pda}`);\n}\n```\n\n## General Structure\n\n1. **Imports** (lines 8-9) — postgres library + utilities\n2. **Type exports** (lines 15-196) — all public types with clear naming conventions\n3. **Helper functions** (lines 200-493) — phase validation, normalization functions\n4. **createDb factory function** (line 492+) — returns a Db interface implementation\n5. **Async methods** — all database operations are async, return Promises\n6. **Exports** — types and createDb function only (no direct sql export)\n\nThis modular pattern keeps the database layer isolated and fully typed!"}],"totalDurationMs":20841,"totalTokens":41500,"totalToolUseCount":1,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14103,"cache_read_input_tokens":25791,"output_tokens":1601,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":14103},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
